    <fr:title text="Equicontinuous">Equicontinuous</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors />
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>A family of functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> from a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d_X)]]></fr:tex> to a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(Y,d_Y)]]></fr:tex> is said to be equicontinuous at a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_0 \in  X]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[δ > 0]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_Y(f(x), f(x_0)) < ε]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \in  F]]></fr:tex> and all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_X(x, x_0) < δ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>The family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is said to be equicontinuous if it is equicontinuous at each point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Intuitively, an equicontinuous family of functions has the property that all functions in the family maintain the same level of continuity uniformly.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
